 {"id":"beads_rust-dl86","title":"[P2] Recursive ready parent filter builds unbounded descendant IN query","description":"Root cause: src/storage/sqlite.rs:2757-2777 handles ready --parent --recursive by calling collect_descendant_ids, then building one or more large id IN (...) clauses in Rust. collect_descendant_ids at src/storage/sqlite.rs:5184-5206 performs a BFS that queries children one parent at a time and returns every descendant ID as a Vec. A deep or wide epic tree can therefore pay O(descendants) DB round trips plus allocate a large Vec, placeholder strings, SQL text, and bind parameter list before SQLite can evaluate the ready query.

Repro: create a 10k issue parent-child tree and run br ready --parent <root> --recursive --json. Compare against the Ready (10k issues / 20k deps) scenarios already in benches/storage_perf.rs; the recursive parent case is not covered by those targets and should show much worse planning/allocation behavior.

Proposed fix: push recursive parent expansion into SQLite with a recursive CTE if fsqlite supports it, or use a temporary descendant table/chunked join strategy that avoids one query per parent and avoids synthesizing a giant IN predicate. Keep all user values bound parameters.

